SIMPLE: tuft
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tuft
<hw>Tuft</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>tuff</ets>, F. <ets>touffe</ets>; of German origin; cf. G.
<ets>zopf</ets> a weft of hair, pigtail, top of a tree. See <er>Top</er>
summit.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A collection of small, flexible, or soft
things in a knot or bunch; a waving or bending and spreading cluster;
<as>as, a <ex>tuft</ex> of flowers or feathers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cluster; a clump; <as>as, a <ex>tuft</ex> of
plants</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Under a <qex>tuft</qex> of shade.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Green lake, and cedar <qex>fuft</qex>, and spicy glade.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A nobleman, or person of quality, especially in the
English universities; -- so called from the tuft, or gold tassel, on the
cap worn by them.</def> <mark>[Cant, Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Several young <qex>tufts</qex>, and others of the faster men.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Hughes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuft</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tuft
<hw>Tuft</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tufted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tufting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate into
tufts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To adorn with tufts or with a tuft.</def>
<rj><au>Thomson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuft</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tuft
<hw>Tuft</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow in, or form, a tuft or
tufts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuf-taffeta</ent>⟦br⟧
